{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20581"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20581"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13458"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93731"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13458"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76941"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12503"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32137"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93731"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAortic dissection is a life-threatening condition where separation of layers within the aortic wall occurs. This creates an abnormal channel for blood flow that can lead to serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathological process in aortic dissection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood enters the media creating a false lumen","Blood accumulates between the adventitia and surrounding tissues","Inflammatory cells infiltrate all layers of the aortic wall","Calcification develops extensively within the intimal layer","Thrombus forms on the damaged luminal surface"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn aortic dissection, \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood enters the media creating a false lumen\u003C/strong\u003E. This typically begins with a tear in the intima, allowing blood to enter the media and split its layers. The blood-filled space within the media is called the false lumen, while the original vessel lumen is termed the true lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood accumulates between the adventitia and surrounding tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes periaortic haematoma, not aortic dissection. In dissection, blood remains contained within the vessel wall layers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory cells infiltrate all layers of the aortic wall\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes aortitis, an inflammatory condition of the aorta. While inflammation may occur secondarily in dissection, it is not the primary pathological process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification develops extensively within the intimal layer\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a feature of atherosclerosis. While atherosclerosis may be present in patients with aortic dissection, calcification is not the defining pathological process of dissection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombus forms on the damaged luminal surface\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes thrombosis on the intimal surface, which is different from dissection. In dissection, the primary event is the separation of medial layers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathological basis for aortic dissection often involves cystic medial degeneration, characterised by the loss of smooth muscle cells and fragmentation of elastic fibres in the media. This weakens the aortic wall, making it susceptible to dissection, particularly in the setting of hypertension which increases wall stress.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aortic dissection occurs when blood enters the media of the aortic wall, creating a false lumen between the intima and adventitia.","Cystic medial degeneration with loss of elastic fibres and smooth muscle cells is the primary histological finding in aortic dissection.","Hypertension is the most common risk factor for aortic dissection, causing increased shear stress on the aortic wall."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 507"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76941"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20581"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76941"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:22:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T18:53:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13458"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93731"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12503